				\begin{document}$$x^{\sum _{j\ne i=1}^{n}p^{(t)}_j} &#x0003e;1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M418"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mo>&#x02211;</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02260;</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>&#x0003e;</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11229_2016_1268_Article_IEq204.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and the subjective probabilities will decrease and this will repeat. Similarly if the majority start by voting correctly the subjective probabilities will decrease until at some stage the majority will assign a probability less than 0.5 to the hypothesis after which they will vote incorrectly and thus the probability assignments will start to increase, etc.</p></sec></app></app-group><fn-group><fn id="Fn1"><label>1</label><p id="Par5">There are various improvements of the result, such as: (1) The conclusion also holds if one makes the weaker assumption that the average reliability of the voters is greater than 1/2. (2) List and Goodin (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR10">2001</xref>) generalized the theorem to cases with more than two choice options. (3) Dietrich and Spiekermann (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR4">2010</xref>) proved a modified version of the Condorcet Jury Theorem where they differentiate between individual dependencies and dependencies on a common cause.</p></fn><fn id="Fn2"><label>2</label><p id="Par7">See Bohman and Rehg (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR2">1997</xref>), Cohen (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR3">1989</xref>), Dryzek (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR6">1990</xref>), Elster (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR7">1998</xref>), Fearon (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR8">1998</xref>), Marti (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR11">2006</xref>), and Nino (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR12">1996</xref>).</p></fn><fn id="Fn3"><label>3</label><p id="Par22">As we disregard strategic considerations in our model, a group member&#x02019;s vote is only determined by the probability the group member assigns to the corresponding proposition.</p></fn><fn id="Fn4"><label>4</label><p id="Par26">We follow the convention used in Bovens and Hartmann (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">2003</xref>). Note that <inline-formula id="IEq95"><alternatives><tex-math id="M419">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r^{(0)}_{ij} \ge 1/2$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M420"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>&#x02265;</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">/</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11229_2016_1268_Article_IEq95.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> implies that <inline-formula id="IEq96"><alternatives><tex-math id="M421">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
